            {
                result.Add(wordBuffer.ToString());
            }
```

Since the `csv.cs` is only called in `GetAliasesFromFile()` in `importAliasCommand.cs`, I'm thinking of refactoring `GetAliasesFromFile()`, which I think can be done in a way in which we don't need the seperate `csv.cs` file. 

It seems `GetAliasesFromFile()` uses readers. This makes sense as a `reader` is able to read a line from a file faster than a `for` loop would be able to. I would say it makes more sense to use a reader as well for the individual line parsing, for the sake of consistency throughout the method. However, according to the discussion on this Pull Requests, using indices are preferred over readers. As I said before, I'm fine with implementing indices instead if that is preferred, but I do want that then we will be mixing two ways of reading which might be more confusing than to use the `reader` for all reading in the method. For now I will assume we prefer to use indices for parsing the individual lines.

Before I start with the actual implementation, I want to know if I'm on the same line as the community by asking if we agree on the following, to prevent working on something which is not according to the standards and guidelines used by PowerShell.

* I want to get rid of having the file called `csv.cs` given its current functionality. I think it is confusing at is is not handling all the csv parsing within PowerShell but does have a very general name. 
* Creating the csv file can be called statically. There is no need to create a CSVhelper object to parse a line in the current implementation.
* A check to Ignore blank lines and comment lines is performed in both CSVhelper and `GetAliasesFromFile()` and could be merged such that there's a single point in the code where this violation is checked.
* `GetAliasesFromFile()` is too long and complex and can be split up. Functions can be created for the subprocesses (such as creating the options, creating the alias, checking for violation), such that we reduce complexity and it becomes easier to understand what the code does.
* the error handling is all over the place and could be replaced by a try catch to keep it centralized and to keep it easy to read what the different error outcomes are and how these are handled.

As a start, I've spent some time to make some pseudo-ish-code based on the current implementation of what I think is a refactor that makes more sense while keeping the functionality intact. If we agree, I'd like to hear if you want me to open a new one or that I should keep working within this PR since it is all related.

```
GetAliasesFromFile() {
    result = new collection()
    // linenumber is used for error handling
    Int lineNumber = 0;

    using (StreamReader reader = OpenFile(out filePath, isLiteralPath)) {
    	linenumber = 0
   	
        while ((line = reader.ReadLine()) != null) {
        	++lineNumber
        	try {
        		// parse the line, throw exception if invalid
		        parsedLine = parseLine(line)

			// check for any further violations which is able to throw an exception
			
			isValidParsedLine(parsedLine)

			// if valid add to results
	    		result.add(constructAlias(parsedLine))
	    	} 
	    	catch (InvalidLineException e ) {
	    		// for some cases, like blank line or commented line, we should do nothing and just skip the line
		    } 
		    catch (ArgumentException e) {
		    	// ArgumentException can happen when the options object cannot be created
		    	// we should write an error, create no alias and continue
		    } 
		    catch (NoFourValuesException e) {
		    	// if not four values, do ThrowTerminatingError(errorRecord) just like old code
		    	// code below is copy pasted from importAliasCommand.cs
		    	string message = StringUtil.Format(AliasCommandStrings.ImportAliasFileInvalidFormat, filePath, lineNumber);

		        FormatException formatException =
		            new FormatException(message);

		        ErrorRecord errorRecord =
		            new ErrorRecord(
		                formatException,
		                "ImportAliasFileFormatError",
		                ErrorCategory.ReadError,
		                filePath);

		        errorRecord.ErrorDetails = new ErrorDetails(message)
			ThrowTerminatingError(errorRecord)
		    }		       	
        }	
    }
    return result
}


